<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-frequency-distribution-tables-grouped" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Frequency Distribution Tables (Grouped)</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        3.0 Statistics and Probability
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        3.1 Statistics 1
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Draw a frequency distribution table for grouped and ungrouped data
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand the purpose of grouping data into class intervals and the structure of grouped frequency distribution tables.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Construct grouped frequency distribution tables with appropriate class intervals, tally marks, and frequencies.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Organise large raw datasets into grouped frequency tables and identify patterns.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/statistics-and-probability/statistics-1/frequency-distribution-tables-grouped.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/statistics-and-probability/statistics-1/step-by-step-guide_frequency-distribution-tables-grouped.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <introduction>
        <p>
            Before we can analyze large datasets, we must first organize them. A <term>Frequency Distribution Table</term> simplifies raw data by sorting it into specific ranges called <term>class intervals</term> (such as <m>0–10, 10–20,</m> etc.). 
        </p>
        <p>
            Instead of looking at a long list of scattered numbers, we count how many data points fall into each interval. This count is known as the <term>frequency</term>. By arranging data this way, we can quickly identify patterns, such as where the majority of the data lies or if there are any outliers, without needing to process every single number individually.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Students work in groups to organize raw data into class intervals and discover how grouping helps reveal patterns in large datasets.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Discussion Prompts</title>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Why is it hard to understand the data when it's jumbled?</p></li>
                <li><p>How does grouping into intervals help us see patterns?</p></li>
                <li><p>What is the lowest score? Highest score? Range?</p></li>
                <li><p>Which interval has the most students? What does this mean?</p></li>
                <li><p>Do we know the exact scores after grouping? What do we lose?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                A mathematics teacher recorded the test scores (out of <m>50</m>) for a class of <m>25</m> students. The raw data is listed below.
            </p>
            <p>
               <alert>Raw Scores:</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                12, 34, 45, 23, 8, 36, 41, 29, 15, 48,
                33, 25, 38, 19, 44, 27, 31, 49, 22, 14,
                5, 42, 39, 28, 35.
            </p>
            <p>
                It is difficult to see how the class performed just by looking at this jumbled list. Let's organize this data into a grouped frequency table to better understand the class performance.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    First, determine the range of the data. Identify the lowest score and the highest score in the list.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Construct a frequency distribution table using class intervals of width <m>10</m>. Use the following intervals: <m>0–9, 10–19, 20–29, 30–39, 40–49</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Create three columns in your table:
                    <ul>
                        <li><alert>Class Interval</alert> (The groups listed above)</li>
                        <li><alert>Tally</alert> (Mark each score in the correct group)</li>
                        <li><alert>Frequency</alert> (Count the tallies for the final number)</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Look at your completed table. Which class interval has the highest frequency? What does this tell you about the overall performance of the class?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concepts of class intervals, class width, grouped frequency tables, and the trade-off between grouping and losing individual data identity.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping data</alert> helps us see patterns and trends in large datasets that would otherwise be hidden. However, once data is grouped into <term>class intervals</term>, we lose the specific identity of the individual numbers. For this reason, calculations performed on grouped data are always considered <term>estimates</term> rather than exact values.
        </p>
    </insight>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To apply the skill of constructing grouped frequency distribution tables with appropriate class intervals.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Work through examples with learners step by step. Circulate during independent practice and provide assistance where needed.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The following data represents the daily earnings (in dollars) of <m>20</m> freelance workers:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>45, 62, 58, 41, 75, 50, 48, 66, 72, 55, 
                43, 60, 52, 78, 49, 64, 57, 70, 44, 69</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Construct a grouped frequency distribution table using class intervals of width <m>10</m>. Start with the interval <m>40–49</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, we define the intervals. Then, we count how many earnings fall into each group.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><alert>40–49:</alert> 45, 41, 48, 43, 49, 44 (<m>6</m> values)</li>
                    <li><alert>50–59:</alert> 58, 50, 55, 52, 57 (<m>5</m> values)</li>
                    <li><alert>60–69:</alert> 62, 66, 60, 64, 69 (<m>5</m> values)</li>
                    <li><alert>70–79:</alert> 75, 72, 78, 70 (<m>4</m> values)</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                The resulting frequency table is:
            </p>
            <table>
                <title>Daily Earnings Distribution</title>
                <tabular halign="center">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                        <cell>Class Interval ($)</cell>
                        <cell>Frequency (<m>f</m>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>40–49</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>50–59</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>60–69</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                        <cell><m>70–79</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><alert>Total</alert></cell>
                        <cell><alert>20</alert></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The marks obtained by 40 students in a mathematics test are:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>42, 55, 47, 61, 50, 38, 44, 49, 54, 60,</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>41, 48, 52, 46, 57, 51, 39, 62, 45, 58,</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>43, 56, 54, 59, 63, 40, 37, 64, 36, 65,</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>47, 49, 50, 52, 55, 51, 48, 53, 60, 61</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Using <m>6</m> class intervals, construct a frequency distribution table.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To construct a frequency distribution table, we do the following
            </p>
        
            <p>
                <ol marker="Step 1:">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <term>Determine the range</term>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Maximum value <m>= 65</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Minimum value <m>= 36</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Range <m>= 65 - 36 = 29</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <term>Decide class width</term>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Number of classes <m>= 6</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Class width <m>=</m> Range <m>\div</m> Number of classes <m>= 29 \div 6 \approx 4.83 </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We can therefore use a class width of <m>5</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <term>Complete the frequency table</term>
                        </p>
                        <tabular left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium" top="medium">
                            <row header="yes">
                                <cell>Class Interval</cell>
                                <cell>Frequency (f)</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>36-40</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>14-45</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>46-50</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>9</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>51-55</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>9</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>56-60</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>61-65</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                            </row>

                        </tabular>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete exercises.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-frequency-distribution-table-for-grouped-data">
        
        <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Consider the following frequency distribution table representing the ages of members in a chess club:
                    </p>
                    <table>
                        <title>Chess Club Ages</title>
                        <tabular halign="center">
                            <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                                <cell>Age Group</cell>
                                <cell>Frequency</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>10-19</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>20–29</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>12</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>30–39</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                    <p>
                        How many members are in the chess club in total, and how many members are aged <alert>20 or older</alert>?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        Total members: <m>8 + 12 + 5 = 25</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Members aged <m>20</m> or older: <m>12 + 5 = 17</m>.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A dataset is grouped into the following class intervals: <m>0–4</m>, <m>5–9</m>, <m>10–14</m>, and <m>15–19</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Determine the <term>class width</term> of these intervals. (Hint: Be careful not to just subtract the limits; count the number of values included in the interval).
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        The class width is <m>5</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        (For example, the interval <m>0–4</m> includes the values <m>0, 1, 2, 3,</m> and <m>4</m>).
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The following is a list of distances (in km) cycled by a group of students over a weekend:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        5, 12, 8, 24, 15, 9, 28, 11, 6, 21
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Construct a frequency table with the class intervals: <m>0–9</m>, <m>10–19</m>, and <m>20–29</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <table>
                        <title>Cycling Distances</title>
                        <tabular halign="center">
                            <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                                <cell>Distance (km)</cell>
                                <cell>Frequency</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0–9</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>10–19</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>20–29</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                </answer>
            </exercise>

            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A researcher surveyed <m>50</m> households about their monthly electricity usage. The data was grouped into a frequency table, but one value was erased by accident.
                    </p>
                    <table>
                        <title>Electricity Usage</title>
                        <tabular halign="center">
                            <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                                <cell>Usage (kWh)</cell>
                                <cell>Frequency</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0–100</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>101–200</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>18</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>201–300</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>301–400</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                    <p>
                        Calculate the missing frequency <m>x</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        We know the total frequency is <m>50</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>5 + 18 + x + 7 = 50</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>30 + x = 50</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>x = 20</m>
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn frequency table templates with intervals already filled in. Use smaller datasets (10–15 values) to build confidence. Provide coloured highlighters to mark data points as they are tallied. Work in pairs with peer support. Use physical objects (cards with numbers) that can be physically sorted into groups. Provide step-by-step worksheets with guided practice.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Explore larger datasets (50+ values) with more intervals. Investigate how changing class width affects the table and patterns. Compare grouped vs ungrouped data — what information is lost? Create their own datasets and determine appropriate intervals. Research real-world applications: census data, market research, quality control.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
